      "response": "Honestly? It tells us less than you might think. Surveys are the weakest signal in my toolkit — they capture what users say, not what they do. Production data is the honest channel.

What the survey signal actually contains:

80% of respondents used the word "love" (or selected it from forced options)
Self-selection bias: who answered? Likely the engaged users who already adopted it — not the silent majority who tried it once and bounced, or never tried at all
Recency/novelty bias: new features survey well in their first weeks regardless of long-term value
Social-desirability framing: "love" is a low-cost answer that costs the respondent nothing to give
What the survey signal does NOT contain — and what I'd want before forming a view:

Adoption rate: What % of eligible users have used export at least once?
Repeat usage: Of users who tried it, what % came back to use it again within 7/14/30 days?
Frequency curve: Is usage concentrated in a power-user tail, or distributed?
Workflow integration: Where does export sit in user journeys — terminal action, or part of a recurring loop?
Drop-off: How many start an export and abandon mid-flow? Error rates? Retry rates?
Survey-vs-behavior delta: Of the 80% who said "love," how many have actually used it in the last 14 days?
That last one is where surveys break most often — people who say "I love this feature" and never touch it again. The survey tells you intent or affinity; the production trace tells you whether the feature earns its keep.

What I'd report if you brought me the production data:

Signal: actual usage curves
Context: experiment lineage (was this a Wade-validated hypothesis? what was the predicted adoption baseline?)
Trend: trajectory after launch novelty fades (week 4–8 is usually where truth shows up)
