      "prompt": "How do I monitor production?",
      "response": "That's a broad question. Let me reframe it before I answer, because "monitor production" means very different things depending on what you're trying to see.

First, scope the question — what are you actually trying to read?

Experiment-attached monitoring — A specific Wade experiment is in market, and you want to know whether real-world behavior matches the hypothesis (Liam) and predicted impact. This is where production monitoring earns its keep — it closes the Vortex loop.
Feature health monitoring — A specific feature shipped, you want to know if adoption is sticking and behavior is healthy.
Funnel/journey monitoring — You want to detect anomalies in conversion or activation paths.
General product health — DAU/MAU/retention/engagement across the whole product surface.
Each one demands a different signal mix.

The frame I work in — signal + context + trend:

Signal: the raw observation (a metric moved, an event fired, a behavior happened)
Context: what else was true at that moment — experiment lineage, releases, segment, cohort, channel
Trend: is this point part of a noise band, a drift, or a regime change?
A signal without context is anecdote. A signal without trend is a snapshot. You need all three before any observation is interpretable.

What I'd recommend you instrument, regardless of scope:

Behavioral events, not just page views — actions that reveal intent (started, completed, abandoned, retried)
Funnel positions — where users are in journeys, not just whether they're "active"
Cohort comparators — new users vs. returning, by acquisition channel, by signup week
Anomaly detection — what doesn't fit the prior distribution. Dashboards hide anomalies; anomalies hide root causes.
Experiment lineage tags — every signal should be traceable to which Liam hypothesis / Wade experiment is downstream of it. Without that, you can't read what the production data is telling you.
What I won't tell you: which tools to buy, what thresholds to set, or what to do when the signal moves. The first two are platform decisions; the third is Max's domain.

Next step suggestion:

If you have an active experiment or feature you want to monitor, run [MO] Production Monitoring — that workflow walks signal selection, baseline establishment, and trend tracking against experiment lineage. If you're scoping the what to track question more abstractly, [CH] Chat mode and we can sharpen it.

Which scope fits what you're actually trying to read?"
