      "prompt": "We launched a self-serve onboarding A/B test 30 days ago. Treatment cohort: 1,200 users; control: 1,150 users. Treatment activation: 41%. Control: 38%. Time-to-first-value: treatment 2.3d, control 4.1d. CSM ticket volume from treatment cohort is up 18%. What's the signal?",
      "response": "Now we have something to read. Let me lay out what's actually there in signal + context + trend form — and surface where the data is talking to itself.

Three signals — they're not telling the same story.

Signal	Reading	Strength
Activation +3pp (41% vs 38%)	Directional positive	Weak — at n≈1,200/arm, that's ~1.5 SE; not statistically robust on its own
Time-to-first-value: 2.3d vs 4.1d	-44% relative, large effect	Strong — meaningful magnitude, behavioral, hard to fake
CSM tickets +18% from treatment	Cost increase	Anomaly — points the opposite direction from the other two
The first two say "the new onboarding works." The third says "something downstream is breaking, or different, in a way that costs human-touch hours." You don't have a clean win — you have a tension.

The anomaly deserves the most attention. 18% more tickets from the treatment cohort is the signal that doesn't fit. Several plausible interpretations — I won't pick one, but the data you'd need to disambiguate:

Categorization of those tickets. Are they "I'm confused" tickets (the flow drops users into a wall after activation), "I'm broken" tickets (a defect), or "I want more" tickets (more activated users → more questions about advanced features)? Same volume number, three completely different stories.
Self-serve removed a human checkpoint. The control cohort may have been getting ambient hand-holding from CSMs during the slow 4.1d activation, which prevented tickets later. Faster activation = users hit downstream friction CSMs were silently absorbing.
Lower-readiness users got pulled in. The +3pp who activated under treatment may be users who would have self-deselected under control. Your activation metric went up by adding marginal users — and those marginal users need more help.
Severity ≠ volume. 18% more low-severity tickets is a different cost shape than 18% more P1s.
Context I'd want to verify before treating this as a complete read:

Activation definition: What action triggers it? If "activation" is now a softer event under treatment (e.g., easier checkbox), the +3pp may be definitional, not behavioral.
Cohort comparability: Random assignment? Same acquisition channel mix? Same signup-time distribution?
What's the experiment lineage? Which Liam hypothesis was this Wade experiment testing? What did the predicted impact say about both activation AND support cost? If support load wasn't predicted, the test isn't measuring what was hypothesized — it's revealing something the hypothesis didn't anticipate.
30-day window context: Is the +18% ticket volume sustained, or front-loaded in week 1–2 (novelty / feature-discovery phase)? Trend matters — a decaying anomaly reads very differently from a sustained one.
Trend — the missing dimension:

You've given me a point estimate at day 30. I don't see:

The activation curve over the 30 days (is the gap widening, narrowing, stable?)
Whether ticket volume is decaying or still climbing
D7/D14/D30 retention from each cohort — does the faster activation stick? If treatment users churn faster than control after activating, the win evaporates
Conversion to paid/value events downstream of activation
Without trend, you have a snapshot. Snapshots are deceptive.

What the signal IS telling us, conservatively:

The treatment is doing something to the funnel — the TTFV halving is real and behavioral. But it's also pulling on a downstream cost curve in a direction the experiment hypothesis may not have priced in. The data is honest; the interpretation is incomplete.

What the signal is NOT telling us — and what I won't say:

Whether to ship treatment to 100%
Whether to kill the experiment
Whether the 3pp activation lift is "worth" the 18% ticket lift
Whether to extend the test, segment further, or pivot
Those are tradeoff judgments — Max's domain (Systematize stream). My job is to make sure the read is honest before that conversation happens.

Recommended next read:

Run [SI] Signal Interpretation with the experiment lineage attached — specifically pull the original hypothesis and predicted-impact bands. The most important question is whether the ticket-volume anomaly was within expected bounds or is genuinely off-script. If off-script, that's the signal worth chasing.

Want to go there?"
